column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shippers location to a Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities for continued transportation.  During the course of the transfer operation, the fork-lift operator punctured one of the containers with the drum grabber attachment of the fork-lift.  The transfer operation was immediately suspended while facility personnel initiated clean-up activities.  Using appropriate personnel protective equipment, facility personnel placed the damage container into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent materials used to collect the material that escaped from the package.  This container was secured and transferred to the alternate van trailer for continued transportation.      This incident was reported to the Ohio EPA and was assigned case Number 1006-18-1512.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the fork-lift operator was counseled on the safe operation of mechanical container handling equipment and will receive refresher training on the use of lift equipment outfitted with drums grabbers.

column17: Terminal Railroad Association of St. Louis
column168: On discovery of release responders were contacted to site. Inspoection of release indicated a UTLX 902455 loaded with Methyl Methacrylate, inspection of the top valve arrangement indicated a "weeping" of the material was coming from a connection with a Cam Lock Cap covering this item. On removal of the Cam Lock a "4" Dry Break Fitting was discovered to have product weeping from the spring area of this fitting which is mounted as one unit on the Top Ball Valve body. As the material weeped from the mentioned area it was noted material was evaporating as quickly as it was weeped. Since the materials needed to repair were not available in house. Chemtrec was contacted who in turn had a representative from Rohm and Haas Chemical Co.contact the Terminal Railroad Association of St. Louis (TRRA) and in turn Rohm and Haas dispatched their Emergency Response group from Louisville Ky. Om arrival their inspection revealed there was material trapped between valve body and the 4" Dry Break Fitting. At this time the car was depressurized and the trap material placed back into the car. The duration of the release on TRRA was approximately 14hrs
column169: Since this is the first time involved with this type of fitting it is very possible while the car was being loaded and the loading process was completed the loader perhaps closed the top body valve prior to prior to diconnecting the 4" Dry Break Fitting thus trapping material between the valve body and the 4" Dry Break Fitting which allowed the material to weep. Perhaps training reminders will help prevent what took place.

A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shippers location to a Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities for continued transportation.  During the course of the transfer operation, the fork-lift operator positioned the forks under a pallet that was being moved to the trailer used to consolidate the shipment.  When the pallet as elevated it broke allowing one container to fall to the dock floor where the top lid was dislodged allowing material to escape onto the dock floor.  Facility personnel immediately placed the container in an upright position and initiated clean-up procedures.  Using appropriate personnel protective equipment, facility personnel placed the damage container into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent materials used to collect the material that escaped from the package.   This container along with two other containers of clean-up debris were secured and transferred to the alternate van trailer for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility.      This incident was reported to the Louisiana State Police Right to Know Unit and was assigned incident Number 10-03040.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, facility personnel involved in the management and transfer of containers for continued transportation have been cautioned to not only inspect the structural integrity of each container being handled for transportation but to also inspect the loading devices used to consolidate 2 or more containers.  This includes a review of the integrity of pallets as well as insuring there are no protruding nails or other sharp edges that could compromise the integrity of the pallet.

During normal switching operations at the UPRR Livonia, LA yard, employees observed a small vapor release from the top of the tank car. The vapor cloud dissipated with no injuries or exposures. The car was isolated and UPRR HazMat Mgr T. M. Robinson responded and inspected the tank car. This inspection revealed that although the car was not actively leaking, a small amount of the tank cars contents had released from the manway nozzle. Robinson conferred with Mr. Chad Blake of Bayer, the shipper and a technician from U.S.E.S was dispatched. Mr. Kelsey Templet of U.S.E.S checked all of the bolts and nuts and tightened several, although none were inordinately loose. The car was moved to simulate a sloshing motion with no further release detected. Templet cleaned the spillage from the tank using a mild basic solution.
column169: Shipper to review tank car closure and securement procedures with appropriate personnel.

column168: During a routine inspection it was discovered that liquid material was leaking from a loaded trailer into RCRA containment. A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and found that a cubic yard box was leaking. The packages were repacked and area was deconed.  Material was reloaded and continued in transportation
column169: During the response it was discovered that the closure device on a paint can that was collected from a household hazardous waste collection event came  loose during transportation and spilled its contents into the interior of the cubic yard containers. The material leaked through the liner and fiberboard box  onto te floor of the van trailer. In order to prevent a recurrence, the field crew responsible for laoding this container have been re-instructed on the terms  and conditions of the DOT Special Permit authorizing this packaging methodolgy. Specifically, it was stressed that all containers must be secured, loaded  in such a way to prevent movement within the package and packaged in such a way to insure they remain upright within the outer container.

column168: A BNSF switch crew in the railyard reported UELX 78039 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. BNSF and contract responders inspected UELX 78039 finding the leak source at the bottom outlet closure cap (BOC). Responders also noted that the bottom operated BOV's operating handle was pinned in a closed position but was mobile, which may have allowed the valve to open slightly. The responders tool tightened the BOC one full turn and inserted a wooden wedge against the valve's operating handle to keep it from moving from the closed position. Afterwards, no further product drips were observed and all spillage evaporated. The BOC gasket was not inspected. Response was concluded by 0910 hrs. CDT, 6/01/2010.  Specification stenciling on UELX 78039 indicated a built date of 09/1977 and its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shippers location to a Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location pending a scheduled delivery slot to the intended waste management facility.  While conducting a pre-trip inspection prior to moving the trailer, it was discovered that material had leaked from the trailer onto the ground where the trailer was staged.  Facility personnel activated the in-house spill response team to address the incident.  Using appropriate personnel protective equipment, the response team entered the trailer and identified a 55 gallon non-bulk package leaking from the seam of the container.  Facility personnel isolated the container and placed it into a suitable salvage drum.  In addition, contaminated soil was removed from the trailer parking area and placed into containers for disposal.  Clean fill was spread over the affected area and returned to its normal condition.  The trailer floor was decontaminated and all material generated from this activity was also containerized for disposal. The salvage drum containing the damaged container along with all material generated in the response activities were loaded onto the trailer and sent for disposal at the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation there was no evidence of leaking or damage.  Upon examination of the container during the spill response activities, it was noted that the container used was rated for solids and/or inner containers.  The driver that inspected the container will be re-trained on the container inspection process to insure that container markings are viewed to insure a suitable container was selected.  The shipper will be advised of the incident and will be instructed to insure that every container offered for transportation is suitable for the material being offered for transportation.

column168: On 06/02/10 at 18:07 hours, personnel in the CSXT Rice yard in Waycross, GA discovered GATX 200447, a loaded tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, releasing vapors from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Transammonia, Incorporated was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-06-02-00270).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the release was being emitted from the "A" end liquid line valve stem.  The valve stem packing gland retainer nut was loose 1/4 turn.  The issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to Transammonia representative, Angie King at 813-261-0600.  Eagle/SWS personnel tightened the packing gland retainer nut and a 3/16" wire cable seal (Number CHV203013) was used to secure the protective housing cover.  The leak was secured, the car was decontaminated and released to destination.   This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 296  NARRI:  2(5+9+0) X (2+0) = 56

column168: On 06/06/10 at 08:57 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Tilford yard in Atlanta, GA discovered GATX 71077, a loaded tank car of Phenol, Molten, leaking from the manway area of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Ineos Phenol, Fulton County EMA, GAEPD (Report #62333), NRC (Report #942978) and the USEPA were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-06-06-00016).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway gasket was missing. Eagle/SWS personnel installed a new manway gasket and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 207  NARRI: 5(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: At approximately 2350 hours on Sunday, June 13, PTRA train crew 280 notified the Trainmaster that tank car UTLX 649778 was leaking product from the dome area when the car was moved during normal switching in the yard.  Upon discovery, Valero Marketing and Supply in Houston, TX was called to determine the cause of the leak. The local shift supervisor arrived on scene and determined that product was leaking from the "vent pipe" and was probably an overload. This was not the case. On Monday morning the PTRA Safety Director inspected that car and deterined that the cause of the leak was a defective vaccuum relief valve. Since no product was actively leaking or contacting the ground the car was moved into track 210 next to the access road where repair crews could replace the vaccuum relief valve.  We contacted Valero Marketing and Supply in San Antonio to request that they send a crew out to repair the care. After several calls Valero contracted ULTX rail car repair services to repair the car. UTLX Rail Car arrived on scene Tuesday, June 15 at 8:25 AM. They inspected and replaced the manway gasket and replaced the vacuum relief valve. It was determined that the vaccuum relief valve had a broken spring and was not closing thus allowing product to spray down the side of the tank car when moved. Less than one gallon of product was released. No product was observed ont he ground around the car.
column169: PTRA is sending a letter to customers reminding them that they and their shippers are responsible for the safe and proper loading and securment of tank cars before cars are released to the railroad for transport. We are also evaluating other penalties for tank cars that are involved in NARs on PTRA property.

column168: J.B. Hunt driver arrived at rail to pickup the container.  Driver noticed the leak from the outside of the container and notified both rail and JBHunt personnel.  J.B. Hunt contracted environmental remediation contractors to perform cleanup according to on-scene D.E.P. and E.P.A. directions.  Contractors took photos showing that the two pallets of materials had shifted.  The actual cause of the shift could not be determined.(Supplemental Information) This sections needs to be updated to include the additional information. The hazardous material at issue, Potassium Hydroxide, Sodium Hypochiorite, was contained in the following products — Pink Pot & Pan Detergent. Buffered Ware.wash I)etergent. and All Temp 11.1)., (hereinafter “product”) was manufactured by US Chemical and was shipped from Diversey. Diversey loaded the product onto the J. B. Hunt intermodal trailer. Pacella Trucking Express picked up the trailer and took to the rail where the trailer was placed on a rail car by Norfolk Southern.  The product was shipped under a contract with Diversey, the distributor and was in transit to Perkins Paper in Taunton, MA. The product was offloaded by Norfolk Southern. The J. B. Hunt driver arrived at the rail to pick up the trailer and deliver it to Perkins Paper. The driver noticed the leak from the outside of the trailer and notified both the railroad and J. B. Hunt personnel. J.B. Hunt contracted with an environmental remediation contractor to perform cleanup according to on-scene EPA and DEP directions. On scene personnel observed and photographed the load within the trailer; it was not properly braced and blocked, causing a shift of two pallets of material, involving 72 five gallon containers. It could not be determined when the shift in material took place. J. B. Hunt is the carrier on file. It set up the appointment times and coordinated Pacella Trucking to take the load to the rail. J.B. Hunt did not load, handle or observe the product at any time prior to the discovery of the leak by its operator.

column168: CSXT 259565 (AAR C113, 3-compartment covered hopper) at the railyard's repair track for a truck side frame defect was observed with white crystallized product on the outside of all three bottom outlet chute closures. Non-clear liquid drops were also observed emanating from the bottom outlet closures. Apparently, CSXT 259565 sustained water incursion either prior to loading, during loading or enroute. The water gravitated to the bottom of the interior hoppers and mixed with dry product forming a diluted mineral rich watery mixture that seeped through the closed outlets. Some of this mixture dried on the exterior bottom outlets forming white crystalline stalactite type formations. A shipper contractor cleaned this dried material from the bottom outlet structures, capturing the material in receptacles and this material was later returned to the lading. The top hatchways were inspected and deemed secure. Response was concluded by 1700 hrs. PDT, 6/07/2010.   Later, while CSXT 259565 was still at the repair facility, it was again reported oozing a thick liquid mixture from this hopper's bottom outlets. On 6/10/2010, the same response contractor cleaned this material from the bottom outlets. The bottom outlets were then sealed with 'Plug N Dike' sealant and over sealed with duct tape to ensure a water tight barrier. Afterwards, no further liquid leakage was observed and CSXT 259565 was released to proceed to its destination. This response was concluded by 1730 hrs. PDT, 6/10/2010.

column168: Responder found GATX 52915, Residue Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, UN2055, shipper Lion Copolymer of Baton Rouge, consignee Total Petrochem of Houston, leaking (dripping, 1 QT released) from a 2" plug on the bottom outlet valve (BOV) cap. This plug took 2 turns to be "tool tight", correcting the leak. The BOV is bottom operated and was in the closed and pin position. Also, other findings: protective housing was not secured and the 1" vapor valve plug was loose. The State Police was notified, but their Trooper John Daryies did not respond and was advised by phone. The shipper was contacted and actively responded with KCS to this incident. The defective bottom outlet valve causes this package to be a DOT non-complying hazmat package and will require an FRA one time movement approval to deliver this car to home-shop for repair to the BOV. The car owner, Total Petrochemical is in the process of securing a FRA one time movement approval to deliver this car to home-shop. Carrier will continue to hold car under standard demurrage tariff until advised by car owner of FRA movement approval.      KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 will apply.   KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 Item 260 will apply.  KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9012 Item 260 will apply.    Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated because bulk quantities are provided on shipping paper as "1 Tank Car" per DOT requirements.  Carrier is not provided specific quantity information. This action required by preparer to facilitate data acceptance by DOT IT system edits.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.

column168: Hazmat responders found a defective liquid line valve. This valve was in the closed position but still allowing lading (under pressure, nitrogen blanket) to leak by ball valve and then out of a loose secondary closure plug with no teflon tape applied to the threads. The Plug was applied tool tight with teflon tape stopping the release. Also the vapor secondary closure plug was found loose and without teflon tape (but not leaking). This car is now a DOT non-complying package and cannot proceed to destination.  Shipper will secure a FRA one time movement approval and return tank car to their Port Neches facility to be off loaded. Then car will proceed to home-shop under movement approval for repair to defective liquid line valve. The car should be held at Port Arthur yard in bad order status until shipper secures FRA Movement Approval and provides to carrier to return car to their Port Neches rack to be unloaded.     KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 will apply.   KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 will apply. column168: A Ferguson employee swept and hosed out a UPS trailer on thier property on Thursday the 3rd.  Over the weekend he noticed sunburn like symtoms.  He said he was taking new medications unrelated to this and thought it was a reaction to that.  Monday morning 6/7 he had remembered sweeping up the substance and was sent to rapid care around 8:45 a.m.  His symptoms were red arms and hands, slight swelling and small blisters on fore arms.  It looked like sunburn. He returned to work that morning with a doctor's note not to work for one night.  He was given a steroid shot and cream and told to stay out of the sun.  He returned to work on Tuesday night and worked the rest of the week as scheduled.  His symptoms improved daily and as of 6/10 he was fine.

column168: A rolloff box filled with a hazardous dust was parked in the ten day storage/sampling lot.  A driver was loading the box onto the truck, when the material began coming through a hole in the tarp.  Rainwater had leaked through the hole, causing the dust to become sludgelike.  The weight of the material against the tarp then caused the hole to rip further, spilling approximately 70 pounds onto the ground.  A response crew was notified who shovelled the material back into the box and cleaned up the affected area.  The tarp was disposed of.  The load was then accepted into the intended waste disposal facility.  State of Utah was notified (Ed Costomiris) and NRC incident number 942486
column169: Drivers were cautioned to discontinue using old tarps which show signs of deterioration.  The tarp should have been inspected more closely and not used with the hole in it, causing the rainwater to enter the box. The location is exploring the possibility of using bows with the tarps

column168: During a routine yard check, a pool of liquid was noticed underneath a trailer in the 10 day storage yard at the intended waste disposal facility.  A response team arrived and after donning the appropriate personal protective equipment entered the trailer.  A drum was found to have a pinhole leak at the bottom which caused the leak.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the absorbent material used to clean up the spill, and the contaminated soil and gravel.  The trailer was then moved into the intended waste disposal facility for unloading.
column169: It appeared the drum was punctured by a sharp piece of metal protruding from the trailer floor.  The origin location was cautioned to use better care in inspecting trailers prior to loading.  All appropriate personnel at the location were to be scheduled for retraining.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: During a routine yard check at the ten day storage yard at the intended waste disposal facility, a trailer was noticed to be leaking.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  2 fiber drums were stained on the outside indicating they were leaking.  The leaks were caused by inner containers of materials collected at a household hazardous waste event.  The containers were upside down in the container and not packed in any absorbent inner material.  During the course of transportation, bottles broke and lids came off the containers.  The drums and their contents were overpacked into suitable salvage containers along with the absorbent materials used to clean up the trailer and the gravel below.  The trailer was then transported to the intended waste disposal facility for unloading.
column169: The origin location was notified of the incident and was to meet with the participants in the household hazardous waste event to further train them on proper handling and loading of such materials.

column168: On 06/02/10 at 17:15 hrs., personnel in the car shop at CSXT Barr yard in Riverdale, IL discovered FOBX 90003, a residue tank car of Ethylene, Refrigerated Liquid, venting product  from the top of the car. The car was moved outside to a safe location and the local Fire Department was notified and responded.  The shipper, Forbo Adhesives LLC, ILEPA, ILEMA and NRC were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010060200262).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and noted the car had lost its vacuum between the tank and the shell,  Eagle/SWS personnel vapor flared the car from 75 PSI down to 5 PSI and the leak stopped.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Chris Day (919-433-1298) and Eastman Chemical representative, Jim Sullivan (903-237-9501).  The tank car was secured and released to go to the repair shop. This incident did require a special switching move.     Cause Code: 662  NARRI:  2(4+5+0) X (2+0) = 36
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The pail was dropped during handling causing leakage.  The leakage was contained and the package was repacked.  Undamaged product was returned to the shipper.  The damaged product was properly disposed of in accordance with Federal Regulations.

The driver was hoisting the rolloff box onto the trailer from the ten day staging area of the intended waste disposal facility.  The tarp was covered in rainwater and he had stopped with the box in the air to allow the water to drain off.  While doing this, the load shifted, tearing the tarp and dumping onto the ground.  A response crew was summoned and the material on the ground was loaded back into the box.  The area on the ground was cleaned up and that material was also placed into the box.  The load then was taken to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: An investigation found that the load had apparently gotten wet from the rainwater due to a leak in the tarp.  This caused the material inside to get wet and heavy and shift when the box was lifted.  The tarp leaked due to the fact that while sitting in the yard, the tarp is subjected to rainwater collecting on top and also harsh sunlight, causing the deterioration.  The rolloff boxes are intermodal type boxes where the tarp fits flat.  If the boxes could have bows placed in them to angle off the rainwater, this problem would not have occurred.  Logistics personnel are looking into whether or not this can be done.

The spilled area both inside and outside the trailer was cleaned up with an absorbent material.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the cleanup material.  The trailer was then dispatched to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The trailer was loaded by the generator's personnel.  The driver inspected the drums prior to loading and did not notice any leaking materials.  The customer was notified of the incident and the driver was advised to use better care when inspecting drums for acceptance into transportation.

The spill was contained with absorbent pads and the trailer was then unloaded at the intended waste disposal facility.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the materials used to clean up the spill.
column169: The leak developed in the drum due to a small piece of metal protruding from the side of the trailer.  The personnel at the origin location will be retrained in inspecting trailers prior to loading.

The leaking tote was removed from the load, the discharge chute secured and sealed, reloaded and the load transferred onto a van trailer on a spill containment pan.  The truck then continued on to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

Future loads of this material will not be accepted until the cause of the leaks on these totes is discovered and all boxes are checked.

column168: Driver failed to inspect and close discharge valve prior to loading. When loading facility began to load through top manhole, product discharged through open discharge valve. Driver immediately closed discharge valve stopping the flow. 25 gallons of product was contained in loading containment area. The driver was then instructed to pump out containment area and return to carrier for discharge into normal waste stream. The entire release including remediation took less than 1 hour. The driver has since been warned and instructed about proper pre-trip inspection of CTMV and proper securement of all valves.
column169: Driver was admonished for not following proper procedure. A written warniong was issued to the driver who will be closely monitored for any future occurance.

The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the absorbent material used to contain the spill and the contaminated gravel from under the trailer.  The trailer was then unloaded at the intended waste disposal facility and decontaminated.
column169: It was believed the heat played a part in this leak.  The temperature inside the trailer was in excess of 120 degrees.  The origin location was to notify the shipper to leave room in the drums for possible expansion of the product.

(A)GATX 31731 was envolved in a multi-car mainline derailment resulting in the car coming to rest on its side.Approximately 10 gallons of material was released through the pressure relief device.  The leak was contained and the car was uprighted during wrecking operations.  The contents of the car was transferred to another railcar for further handling.After cleaning and purging the car was scrapped on-site. Evacuation figures are from the Pickens County Emergency Management Agency.  An initial evacuation included 436 residences and lasted approximately 7 hours.  The evacuation was reduced to approximately 35 residences and maintained for an additional 7 hours.  A secondary precautionary evacuation of about 100 residents in the immediate area was initiated during clean-up operations involving two other higher hazard materials lasting about 4 hours. Environemntal remediation activities are continuing. (B)GATX 31954 was involved in a multi-car mainline derailment resulting in the car coming to rest on its side.Approximately 100 gallons of material was released from the manway.  The leak was contained to the site and the car was uprighted stopping the release. After cleaning and purging the car was transported from the site and will be scrapped. Evacuation figures are from the Pickens County Emergency Management Agency.  An initial evacuation included 436 residences and lasted approximately 7 hours.  The evacuation was reduced to approximately 35 residences and maintained for an additional 7 hours.  A secondary precautionary evacuation of about 100 residents in the immediate area was initiated during clean-up operations involving two other higher hazard materials lasting about 4 hours. (C)UTLX 48111 was involved in a multi-car mainline derailment resulting in the car coming to rest on its side. Approximately 19,353 gallons of material was released due to a puncture of the tank shell.  The leak was contained to an area immediately surrounding the derailment site and to an adjacent unpopulated area. After cleaning and purging the car was transported from the site and will be scrapped. Evacuation figures are from the Pickens County Emergency Management Agency.  An initial evacuation included 436 residences and lasted approximately 7 hours.  The evacuation was reduced to approximately 35 residences and maintained for an additional 7 hours.  A secondary precautionary evacuation of about 100 residents in the immediate area was initiated during clean-up operations involving two other higher hazard materials lasting about 4 hours. Environmental remediation activities are continuing. (D)DOWX 73599 was involved in a multi-car mainline derailment resulting in the car coming to rest on its side. Approximately 1000 gallons of material was released from the bottom outlet valve as a result of the valve operating handle being damaged and partially opened allowing material to escape from the internal bottom outlet valve.  The exterior auxilliary valve was sheared of

column168: The shipment of hazardous waste had been unloaded onto the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  A routine check of the dock showed a small amount of material had leaked from one drum onto the dock floor.  A response crew was notified.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container, along with the absorbent pads used to clean up the spill.  The drum was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: Investigation of the incident found that the drum was suspected of being in less than good condition for transportation at the time of pickup.  The drum was inspected at the time and not found to be leaking.  The chemists watched the drum for a period of time prior to acceptance.  They were both given verbal warnings for not reporting the situation to their supervisor at time of pickup.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman inspecting an outbound train in the railyard reported a strong product odor emanating from entrained UTLX 78762 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car). No liquid release was observed. The VRV appeared not fully seated with the stem off-center. The responders worked this valve until the valve reseated; and the vapor hiss ceased and the product odor dissipated. Afterwards, the responders were satisfied that the VRV was now functioning as intended. All other fittings were inspected and found secure.

DOT reort # is E-2010060471    Ebasis to follow.

column168: At approximately 3:00 PM on 6/24/10 Airgas Specialty Products driver Mark Calvelage was unloading Ammonium Hydroxide from unit # a-75 into Tank #4 at Progress Energy/Hines Energy in Bartow, Florida the delivery hose camlock came loose causing the hose to disconnect from the "T" adapter. Mark immediately stopped the pump and shut off the valves with the E-Stop which immediately stopped the release. Approximately 5 gallons of 29% Ammonium Hydroxide was released onto the pavement at the customer sight. Mark notified the closest operator who then notified the safety department at Progress Energy. Progress Energy's Environmental personnel were called to the scene to hosed down the release. Mark was informed by Progress Energy personnel that an incident report would be initiated and he was given permission to leave the scene.
column169: Driver was instructed to review ASP's Safe Operating Procedure A-17 (Ammonium Hydroxide Cargo Transport Deliveries) Velcro straps are to be used to properly secure all Cam-loc connections on every Ammonium Hydroxide delivery.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery to Tidewater Supply Co. approximately 200-400 gallons of product were released.  Apparently the release was the result of a fitting on the outlet of the Tidewater Supply Co. tank, cracking and failing.  The product filled the containment area, resulting in the containment area overflowing.  The free product  impacted a nearby drainage ditch.  Liquid Cargo, Inc. dispatched Miller Environmental Group of Smyrna, Delaware to perform an investigation of the site.    Miller Environmental Group arrived on-site and completed PH testing on the drainage ditch and nearby pond and the results were neutral.      Tidewater Supply Company will coordinate additional site remediation as required.
column169: Since the release was accidental and may have been the result of a fitting on the outlet cracking, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Liquid Cargo, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN  TRANSIT!

column168: On Thursday, 6/10, Clean Harbors was the shipper for 21 x cubic yard containers of waste material from Apollo Metals LTD in Bethlehem, PA.  The material is described by waste profile as "Sodium Carbonate Contaminated with Cyanide," 100% solid.  The constituents are listed as Sodium Carbonate (99.9-100%), with up to 0.002% cyanide contamination.  The waste material was manifested for disposal at the Clean Harbors facility in El Dorado, AR, and was held at the Bridgeport, NJ, 10-transfer facility awaiting outbound shipment.  On the morning of Wednesday, 6/16, 2 of the 21 cubic yard boxes were found to have moisture on the outside of the containers coming from inside the boxes during daily facility inspections.  Local Clean Harbors emergency response personnel donned the proper PPE and transferred the material to drums and packaged for disposal all portions of the original containers.  During the transfer of material, they noted moisture in the material (similar to a hard-pack snow, little to no free liquid).  The remaining 19 containers were fully inspected on all outer surfaces for any signs of exterior moisture and the containers were then opened to confirm that there was a liner in place and the material didn't exhibit any form of moisture as found in the failed containers; all 19 containers were found to be in good condition.  All material was shipped on 6/18/10 including the drummed material, debris created from the repacking and the original 19 uneffected containers.
column169: With the possibility of moisture in the waste material, it was determined upon consultation with Apollo Metals that all future packaging should be in drums to prevent any possible compromise of the container.

column168: At aproximately 2:10 pm on a routine walk through inspection a leaking drum in CHES trailer 6347. Upon investigation and speaking with the driver and going over the drivers load sheet it was determined that the leaking material was coming from a US Surgical Drum. The State of CT Spill Response, Bristol Fire Dept. and Field Service were phoned immeidiately. Poly was put under the trailer to collect any spilled material that may seep out. There was nothing collected it did not leave the trailer. A Clean Harbor response team donned the proper PPE and overpacked the drum along with absorbing the spilled material and decontaminating the trailer. Upon examination the drums bung was tight but the gasket had detiriorated causing the leakage.
column169: The customer was notified of the defective drum and spoke to the waste room manager. Upon investigation the drums were checked and the bungs were tightened prior to the Clean Harbors arrival for the pick up. The waste room manager was advised to follow proper closure instructions regarding further drum shipments and will check all gaskets moving forward.

column168: 6/23/10 1745 hrs Upon a load check the driver noticed liquid dripping from the trailer near the landing gear. column168: During a BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard, intermodal container JBHU 246339 loaded atop an entrained intermodal flatcar was reported emanating a chemical odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder opened the container doors and inspected the interior of JBHU 246339. The responder also reported a strong odor emanating from within this container and observed a wet spot atop the container floor. The intermodal flatcar with JBHU 246339 aboard was set-out from the train for a detailed inspection. A BNSF contractor working on site was contacted to ascertain and remedy any possible leak source within JBHU 246339.  The contractor reported finding a palletized 5 gallon poly drum had leaked some contents via its capped bung hole. An apparent load shift caused side contact into this drum from an adjacent larger/heavier drum which forced product out from around the capped bung hole. The spillage was neutralized and wiped. The palletized lading was resecured to prevent further incidents from load shifting

column168: Driver started to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank but forgot to close the petcock on the transfer pump resulting in the first spill. Not sure if the customer valve was open at this time creating undue pressure on the hose or if the hose had a weak spot. The driver then reported he wasn't feeling well due to the heat and his leg was becoming irritated where the product had soaked through his nomex suit. He showered and then was taken to the hospital to be checked out.  A chest x-ray was taken, he was given a steroid and tetanus shot and released.  He was given a full release back to work.  No lost time.

At 0402AM, It appears the vehicle left the road suddenly but gradually. All 18 wheels were off the pavement before the driver steered it back toward road. Somewhere near the tractor reaching the road, the unit rolled onto the passenger side. The truck and trailer slid toward the median in a counter clockwise motion and rested covering both north bound lanes and partially in the median. The unit rested on its passenger side, facing a SE direction. The 911 call came in at 0408.

column168: Swissport forklift driver from the midnight shift accidentally struck and caused a minor puncture to a drum, causing approximately a half gallon worth of spillage of a class 9 substance ( UN 3082 ). After puncturing the drum, the agent instinctively acted to isolate the shipment out side the cargo warehouse and out of harms way. He then reported to his superior. Spillage was contained with speedy dry sand where the incident occurred.      Swissport driver was made aware of the importance to report a DG spillage or damage of any kind immediately, while ensuring the area is isolated and out of any harms way.    All agents and drivers in every work area have been advised to use additional caution when working with and around any dangerous goods shipments, while at the same time reiterating the importance to report an incident immediately to their superiors as proper protocol to be followed within company and DG specification guidelines.

column168: On 06/17/10 at 10:13 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Sibert yard in Mobile, AL, discovered PLMX 135010, a residue tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking vapors from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Transammonia, Inc, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report# 2010-06-17-00199).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product vapors coming from the vapor valve which was slightly open and the vapor valve plug was out.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ms. Angie King (813-261-0600).  Eagle/SWS personnel closed the vapor valve and installed the valve plug wrench tight.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.      This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.     Cause Code: 390  NARRI: 5 (4+9+2) x (2+0) = 150

column168: Upon opening the door of the trailer at it's destination service center in Renton, WA, it was discovered that a pallet of 5 gallon pails and jugs had fallen over inside the trailer. The pallet had been crushed under the weight of 2 other pallets that were stacked on top of it. The pails spilled out from under the other pallet an fell onto the floor of the trailer during transit. Due to the presence of a strong odor, the dockworkers were instructed to stay away from the trailer until I had contacted Chemtrec to determine if it was safe for us to clean up. They cleared us to do so. Upon restacking of the jugs, it was discovered that only a minute amount of liquid had escaped from one of the screw on caps. The jug was set upright and the cap secured. The product was then set on for delivery to the destination customer. The spilled liquid was cleaned with absorbent, and was placed in a receptacle for used absorbent.Chemtrec # 2010061500139

column168: Driver was at the point of delivery.  He had taken one of the two drums into the Central Heating Plant and was on his way in with the second drum.  Upon getting to the garage door, the drum dolly got hung up on the lip of the garage floor.  Driver pushed it back and then pulled it hard to get the drum dolly up on the lip.  The drum bounced on the drum dolly and then tilted slightly and then ended up puncturing the drum on the lower side.  Driver immediately had the reciever help him get drum off of the drum dolly and flipped on side to stop the spillage.  All the spillage (approximately two gallons) was contained on a concrete floor.  The local fire department responded and under direction of the shipper cleaned up the spilled material.  Customer kept all the product and the cleaned up material.  Due to material being a poison, the markings were not able to be obtained off of the drum.  Additionally, it is not known 100% if the feet of the drum dolly were not properly placed under the drum or if the bouncing or another item (such as a bolt on drum dolly) actually punctured the drum.
column169: Drivers are trained in use of drum dolly and other freight handling equipment.  When the driver realized he was having an issue getting the second drum over the concrete lip, for whatever reason, he should have obtained assistance to both steady the drum and to push it up and over the lip.  To push and then pull it harder to get it over the lip risk injury and obviously a greater risk for an incident.

column168: Driver had finished unloading and was preparing to disconnect.  He was bleeding off the pressure through the bottom bleeder valve and was standing down-wind.  He evidentally did not bleed all the pressure off so when he uncoupled from the valve a light mist sprayed up under his face shield and got on his face.  He was wearing all of the proper personal protective equipment except he wasn't wearing his goggles as we require.  None thankfully got in his eyes.  It did get on the skin on his face.  Because the mist was so light he said he didn't take it as a real concern and finished disconnecting, drove to the nearest truck stop, entered the bathroom and found that his face was bright red and that he was out of breath.  He notified us and we immediately had him contact an ambulance to come bring him in for evaluation.  He was given an inhalor and some topical creme.
column169: In this example nothing failed from an equipment perspective.  This falls back on driver training.  He has been brought back in and interviewed.  He was then run through Performance Enhancement Training outlining our personal protective equipment requirements as well as the proper procedures for unloading.  Standing downwind was not the right choice.  We believe this will be an isolated incident with the driver.

column168: On 06/15/10 at 17:00 hours, personnel in the CSXT West Springfield yard in West Springfield, MA, discovered NATX 300695, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. A CSXT conductor was splashed with product but did not require or seek medical attention, as he showered and returned to work. The car was isolated and the shipper, Illinois Corn Processing LLC (subsidiary of MGP Ingredients) was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-06-15-00224).   Environmental Products + Services Inc. (EP+S) of Vermont, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to make repairs.  Upon arrival, EP+S representatives found 3 manway cover bolts were less than hand tight, 2 bolts on the liquid line flange were less than hand tight and the manway cover gasket had deteriorated.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Dan Nolan (913-426-5457).  EP+S personnel tightened the manway cover bolts and the bolts on the liquid line flange tool tight.  EP+S did not have the correct size replacement manway cover gasket and cut one to fit.  The leak was secured and the car was set aside for the shipper to replace the manway gasket.    This incident did require a special shipping move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 (3+3+0) x (2+2) = 120

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper's location to the intended waste managment facility.  During the course of the trip, the vehicle stopped at a Clean Harbors' in transit storage facility.   During the course of the layover, a routine facility inspection identified a container on the vehicle had over pressurized resulting in the package failure.  Facility personnel assembled an emergency response crew and proceeded to place the damaged container into a suitable savage drum.  Absorbent material was used to absorb all free liquids which was recovered and placed into the salvage drum.  Finally the floor of the van trailer was decontaminated and all spill debris was placed into the salvage drum and secured for disposal.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the profile used to approve this waste for transportation and disposal was expired pending confirmation from the shipper that they have identified the constituent that caused the over pressurization.   In addition, the shipper has been advised to insure the containers selected were prepared in accordance with the regulations and were rated for the material in question and are compatible with the lading.  Finally, the driver that accepted the waste material for transportation will be required to attend an on-line refresher training module of container selections, preparation and inspection.

column168: A concerned citizen reported to BNSF that a tank car in the railyard across the street from their location was venting. Immediate inspection by BNSF local operating and mechanical personnel revealed TILX 199866 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard venting from the top fitting area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder's detailed inspection revealed the product was being expelled from the liquid valve's threaded pipe connection and was evaporating on the side shell. The liquid valve was in the closed position. The responder reduced internal pressure within TILX 199866 via the vapor valve and the product release subsided. The responder removed the liquid valve's handle allowing the responder to tool tightened the threaded liquid valve by almost two full turns. Securement was completed by 1700 hrs. PDT, 6/11/2010 when no further product release was observed. Spillage on the tank shell that didn't fully evaporate was wiped with paper towels.   TILX 199866 is currently being held awaiting FRA movement approval for furtherance.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Material handler was attempting to move a pallet of drums from trailer to remove freight in receipt of delivery.  While attempting to drive to pallet the forklift slipped and forks punctured drum of Aluminum Chloride. A gash approximately 8 inches in length was created on the drum approximately 2 inches from the bottom of the drum.   Pallet of drums then picked up and moved to containment area.  Approximately 20-25 gallons of material was released to trailer floor and concrete drive under trailer.  Released material was contained using absorbent pads and socks.  Once released material was contained a Hazmat Response contractor was called to clean the area.  Freight was removed from trailer and reloaded to a clean trailer, which returned to the Univar facility.  Trailer was cleaned and concrete area was neutralized and cleaned.  Absorbent materials and neutralizing solution were used to clean area.  Concrete area was then pressure washed to remove residue with all rinse water contained and disposed as waste.
column169: Increased awareness on the part of dispatchers to decrease instances where freight would need to be moved within trailer to make deliveries.  In addition, increase drivers’ and forklift operators’ awareness of conditions and freight placement when freight needs to be moved in order to make a delivery.  These items will be addressed through safety training program and monthly safety meetings.

column168: An Alaska Railroad (ARR) crew rejected acceptance in interchange of UTLX 201054 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) that was awaiting pickup on the interchange track for barge transport to Alaska. The ARR crew reported to the BNSF that UTLX 201054 was leaking product from the top fitting area. BNSF responders placed absorbent pads to catch the product drips that were slowly dripping off both sides of UTLX 201054's tank shell. The product leak source was from the liquid valve's threaded connection. A BNSF contract responder checked the internal pressure and product outage within UTLX 201054. The pressure was measured at 5-8 psi with 6 1/2 inches of product outage. The internal pressure was reduced via the vapor valve which ended the product release at the liquid valve connection. The liquid valve was in the closed position and the contract responders removed the liquid valve finding no thread sealant on the threaded connection. All threaded connections were cleaned and new Teflon sealant was applied to the threaded area. The liquid valve was then resecured. Spillage on the side shell of UTLX 201054 was decontaminated with a degreasing agent. Intact seal removed numbered 2573122 and replaced with seal numbered 477313. Response was concluded by 1915 hrs. PDT, 6/23/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: T-832 left the Geismar site with a full load of Hydrogen Fluoride, anhydrous mixture on the night of 6/8/2010. The truck pulled into a truck stop for a brief time at exit 4 near Vinton, LA. A walk around inspection was performed by the driver. He got back on the road heading west. About 25 miles, later a call was received on the CB alerting the driver of smoke coming from his trailer. The driver stopped the truck and saw a fire at the trailer driver side front axle inner tire from the 9 to 2 o'clock position. The fire spread throughout the back-end axle system. A fire extinguisher was used without success. A call was placed for fire equipment to be sent to the scene. 2 fire trucks and a backup water truck provided the necessary capacity to extinguish the fire and wet down the cargo tank. There was no failure of the tank, valves or hoses. No leaks resulted. However, the damage from the fire was such that integrity testing on the tank will be done and all the piping will probably be replaced.It is believed the fire was initiated by excessive heat created by a failure in the braking system. This failure led to a partial brake drag not noticed by the driver (more likely if only one brake is dragging). Heat was created by the friction of the brake liner and the brake drum. The brake drum, which sits inside the inner tire (where the fire was initially noticed), created enough heat to eventually ignite the tire.Brake drag can be caused by several factors. Unfortunately, most of the evidence for this was burned in the fire. Possible component failures that could cause brake drag that were not able to be ruled out are:- Brake Chamber middle seal leak. (HIGH),- Partial activation and sticking of Hand Brake. (MED),- Service Brake Valve leak through. (LOW)
column169: The MC412 cargo tank utilized in Hydrogen Fluoride service did not fail which is a testimony to the effectiveness of the package as designed. Based on the possible causes shown above, the following will be implemented:CAUSES CORRECTIVE ACTIONS Brake Chamber middle seal leak. (HI) Add change out on 5 year PM. column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, a leak was discovered in the trailer.  Free liquid was contained inside the trailer, with the application of absorbent material, and leak was secured.  SafetyKleen of Fresno, California was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, four (4) 5-gallon pails were discovered damaged, which resulted in the release of approximately 20 gallons of corrosive liquid, nos.  Free product was contained to trailer floor.  Safety Kleen proceeded to neutralize the free product, which was then recovered into two (2) 55-gallon drums.  SafetyKleen also pressure washed the trailer floor, and containerized the wash water into one (1) 55-gallon drum.  Three (3) 55-gallon drums were generated during the cleanup.  Disposal was coordinated directly with Safety Kleen in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appesrs to be related to an accident during unloading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Roadrunner Transportation Services, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc driver was loading gas to prepare for a customer delivery when the loading head handle became stucl on the handle pin, causing the valve to partially stick open. The driver immediately grabbed the handle to shut off the flow of product but approximately 20 gallons of fuel spilled into the concrete containment area. The terminal personnel and company driver cleaned up the spill. The terminal manager and company assistant terminal manager were also on site and inspected the clean up. No fuel reached drains or soil. The driver did have some fuel make contact with him and he was able to wash off at the facility's emergency shower. It was later determined that there was a mechanical malfunction with the trailer and the trailer was locked out of the loading facility until it was verified that repairs were made.

column168: THE INCIDENT BEING ADDRESSED WAS A RELEASE OF 13,060LBS (WHICH EQUATES TO APPRO 870 GALLONS) OF MOLTEN SULFUR AT RHODIA'S HAMMOND, IN FACILITY.  THE SCHIBER DRIVER, WHO HAS BEEN WITH SCHIBER TRUCK DO. FOR APPROXIMATELY 3.5 YEARS, ARRIVED AT RHODIA WITH A LOAD OF APPROXIMATELY 3600 GALLONS OF MOLTEN SULFUR AROUND 9PM.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO PREPARE HIS TRAILER FOR UNLOADING AND WHEN HE WENT TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO START ATTACHING THE UNLOADING HOSE HE FOLLOWED PROCEDURES BY FEELING THE CAP OF THE UNLOADING VALVE AND DETERMINED IT TO BE WARM, BUT NOT HOT.  WHEN HE STARTED TO REMOVED THE CAP, SULFUR BEGAN TO FLOW OUT OF THE VALVE.  HE TRIED TO PUSH THE CAP BACK ON BUT WAS UNABLE TO.  AT THIS POINT HE TRIED TO CLOSE THE UNLOADING VALVE, BUT IT WAS ALREADY IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND HE DETERMINED IT MUST HAVE BEEN BOUND UP.  HE THEN RAN TO THE EMERGENCY PHONE AND HAD THE OPERATOR BRING A PIPE WRENCH WHICH HE USED TO TRY AND CLOSE THE VALVE THE REST OF THE WAY BUT WAS STILL UNABLE TO.  AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER NOTICED THE TRAILER WOULD GASP FOR AIR PERIODICALLY AS THE DOME LID WAS STILL IN THE CLOSED POSITION WHICH IS ALSO IN THE WRITTEN PROCEDURES.  DURING ONE OF THESE BRIEF MOMENTS, HE WAS ABLE TO RECONNECT THE CAP TO CONTAIN THE REST OF THE LOAD.  ONCE THE DRIVER WAS EVENTUALLY ABLE TO CAP THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND STOP THE FLOW OF SULFUR HE THEN CONTACTED SCHIBER TRUCK COMPANY AND NOTIFIED THEM OF THE SPILL.  A SCHIBER TRUCK CO. REPRESENTATIVE CAUGHT A FLIGHT TO CHICAGO EARLY THE FOLLOWING MORNING TO MEET WITH RHODIA AND DISCUSS THE SPILL WHICH HAD ENTERED THE STORM DRAIN BY THE UNLOADING AREA AND RAN UNDERGROUND THROUGH THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM.  AN OUTSIDE COMPANY WAS HIRED IN TO CLEANUP THE ENTIRE SPILL.  IT WAS FIRST DISCOVERED UPON INVESTIGATION THAT THE VALVE GEARS WERE WORN AND WHICH IT HARD TO CLOSE.  ONCE THE VALVE GOT INTO A BIND THE SHEAR PIN BROKE FROM THE DRIVER TRYING TO CLOSE IT SO HARD.  THIS BROKEN PIN GOT IN BETWEEN THE GEARS AND MADE IT IMPOSSIBLE TO CLOSE.  ONCE THE DRIVER GOT THE PIPE WRENCH HE TURNED IT SO HARD THAT IT BROKE THE HANDLE AND PUT IT IN A FREE SPIN, AT THIS POINT THE VALVE WAS USELESS AND HAD TO REMAIN IN THE POSITION IT WAS IN WHICH WAS ALMOST CLOSED, BUT STILL ALLOWED SULFUR TO FLOW THROUGH IT.  IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THE VACUUM CREATED BY THE SPILL RUPTURED THE VENT DISC ON TOP OF THE TRAILER ALLOWING AIRE TO BE INTRODUCED TO THE EQUATION.  THIS INCREASED AIRFLOW CAUSED A GREATER FLOW OF SULFUR TO EXIT THE TRAILER AND DELAYED THE GASPS FOR AIR.  THESE DISCS ARE IN PLACE TO PREVENT OVER PRESSURIZATION OF THE TRAILER AND DESIGNED TO BREAK IF TOO MUCH AIR IS INTRODUCED TO THE TANK.  IN THIS CASE, THE RAPID SUCTION EFFECT THAT WAS EXPERIENCED CAUSED THE DISC TO BREAK AS WELL.  HAD THIS DISC NOT RUPTURED THE TRAILER WOULD HAVE GASPED FOR AIR MORE FREQUENTLY AND THE DRIVER WOULD HAVE MOSTE LIKELY BEEN ABLE TO MINIMIZE THE SPILL.  THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN TWO DAYS OFF WHILE WE INVESTIGATED THE SPILL TO DETERMINE
column169: AFTER REVIEWING THE INCIDENT, SCHIBER TRUCK CO. HAS DECIDED TO BEGIN MOUNTING A THERMOMETER ON ALL UNLOADING VALVES SO THAT THE DRIVERS WILL BE ABLE TO TELL IF THERE IS PRODUCT BEHIND THE CAP.  THIS SHOULD PROVE TO BE MORE ACCURATE THAN USING YOUR HAND TO FEEL THE CAP.  IF IT IS DETERMINED THAT THERE IS PRODUCT BEHIND THE CAP, THE LOAD WILL NOT BE UNLOADED, BUT RATHER DROPPED AT THE YARD TO HARDEN AND THEN PUT ON STEAM TO UNLOAD WITH ALL VALVES AND HOSES ALREADY IN PLACE.  IT WAS ALSO DETERMINED THAT RHODIA COULD HAVE LESSENED THE EXTENT OF THE SPILL BY USING DRAIN COVER MATS THAT MANY FACILITIES USE TO PREVENT THIS EXACT SAME INCIDENT.  HAD THE SPILL BEEN CONTAINED TO THE CONCRETED AREA THE SPILL CLEANUP WOULD HAVE BEEN MUCH EASIER, QUICKER, AND LESS COSTLY TO CLEAN UP.

column168: A citizen reported that a BNSF train passing through Vinita, OK had an entrained tank car emanating a vapor from the top of this tank car. The crew on a BNSF train in a nearby siding confirmed via a roll-by inspection that the suspect train had entrained UTLX 951443 (DOT 112J400W tank car) emanating a vapor from a top fitting. Train was stopped and held at Catale, OK for inspection by hazardous material responders. BNSF contract responders reported that the pressure relief device (PRD) had allowed product to escape and that the product vapor release had ebbed after the product's auto-refrigerating process occurred. The responders successfully applied a capping kit to fully enclose and seal off the PRD. FRA Movement Approval FRA-0620001V was received to transport UTLX 951443 to the next rail terminal (Tulsa, OK) for product transfer and PRD replacement. UTLX 951443 arrived at the BNSF Tulsa railyard without further incident. On 6/22/2010, BNSF contract responders off-loaded product within UTLX 951443 into tanker trucks. After UTLX 951443 was unloaded, responders flared-off remaining product inside UTLX 951443. The failed PRD had a broken stem at the lower threaded portion of the stem shaft. The PRD spring, follower and the broken bottom stem shaft piece with associated nut hardware still attached were fished out from the bottom of the empty tank. Later on 6/22/2010, a shipper contractor installed a replacement PRD onto UTLX 951443. FRA Movement Approval FRA-10060384 was received to transport UTLX 951443 to a repair facility for furtherance.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: PPRX 29400 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported hissing product vapor from the manway area atop this tank car. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected PPRX 29400 and detected a slight product odor at ground level next to  PPRX 29400. Also, product vapor hissing was audible at the manway closure. The manway securement bolts were tool tight and the manway gasket seal was suspected as the pathway of the product vapor release. PPRX 29400 was then carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. On 6/29/2010, BNSF contract responders were called to assist in stopping the vapor release. The responders reduced the internal pressure (measured at 5 psi) via the vapor line in order to inspect the manway gasket. The manway gasket was found to be in a deteriorated condition and falling apart. A new manway gasket was applied and the manway was resecured. The closure plug on the vapor line was cleaned, new thread sealant applied and resecured. Afterwards, no further product odor or vapor release was detectable. The responders returned the next morning (6/30/2010) to recheck PPRX 29400. Internal pressure within PPRX 29400 was still holding at 0 psi and no product vapor was detectable on the air monitoring devices utilized (4 gas/PID). The new seal applied to the manway cover was numbered 477317 and the new seal applied to the valve housing cover was numbered 477319. The side specification stencil on PPRX 29400 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005 and next due in 2015.

THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING SHIPPER NOTIFICATION FOR A DISPOSITION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver was completing a gasoline truck to truck fueling transaction. Driver encountered no pressure at nozzle while fueling. This phenomenon happens routinely as a result of electronic failure of pumping equipment. Driver trouble shot electronic equipment but still could not create pressure at the fueling nozzle. After additional investigation, driver observed that there was a rupture in the hose beneath the truck from the pump to the discharge meter. The rupture was approximately 3 inches long adjacent to where the hose is connected to a factory manufactured fitting. At that point the driver shut down truck and pump and secured the area to keep all personnel from the area until proper response people arrived at site. Duration of leak was approximately 5 to 10 minutes.

column168: On 06/16/10 at 17:03 hrs., CSX Transportation personnel reported that train Q14916 was involved in a derailment at Milepost BI 227.6 in Portage IN.  Container FCIU 892988, a load of Hazardous Material Polymeric Beads in super sacks, released approximately 22,000 pounds of product.  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to conduct clean-up and disposal activities.  Eagle/SWS personnel removed the product from the derailment site to staging and storage, for return to shipper and proper disposal.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector reported finding eight tank cars in the railyard that he inspected with numerous securement deficiencies and evidence of product leakage. These eight tank cars were all loaded by the same shipper's service provider (Red River Supply at Williston, ND).  Later, this FRA Inspector's follow-up inspection at the Red River Supply's facility at Williston, ND revealed that Red River's personnel had no documented hazardous material training, were not familiar with the applicable hazardous material regulations and deficient in their inspections of their outbound hazardous material shipments.    (Tank Car 1)NATX 303910 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was inspected and found with the liquid valve's closure plug, the vapor valve's closure plug and the sample line's closure plug not tool tight (hand tightened only). Also, 1 of 6 manway securement bolts was found not tool tight (hand tightened only). Product spillage residue was noted around the top valve fitting area near the liquid valve's plug location. After notification of these deficiencies, BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders secured all the loose fittings reported by the FRA Inspector. (Tank car 2)NATX 303953 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was inspected and found with the liquid valve's closure plug, the vapor valve's closure plug and the sample line's closure plug not tool tight (hand tightened only).  Product spillage residue was noted around the top valve fitting area near the liquid valve's plug location. After notification of these deficiencies, BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders secured all the loose fittings reported by the FRA Inspector. (Tank Car 3)SHPX 205265 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was inspected and found with the liquid valve's closure plug and the vapor valve's closure plug not tool tight (hand tightened only). Also, the bottom outlet's closure cap was found not tool tight (hand tightened only). Product spillage residue was noted around the top valve fitting area near the liquid valve's plug location. After notification of these deficiencies, BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders secured all the loose fittings reported by the FRA Inspector. (Tank Car 4)NATX 303912 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was inspected and found with the liquid valve's closure plug and the vapor valve's closure plug not tool tight (hand tightened only). column168: On 6/24/10 at 09:16 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Willard yard, Willard, OH, discovered   UTLX 130023, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Olin Corp., Ohio EPA (RPT# 1006-39-1831), NRC (RPT # 945283) were notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-06-24-00097).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the leak coming from the sump area and placed a hammock under the car to contain the product.  Eagle/SWS personnel pumped the recovered product into poly drums.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Rich Ohara (716-628-4873). The product owner, Reagent Chemical, contacted SPSI to transfer the product and decontaminate the car. The leak was contained and the remaining product was transferred into tank car TILX110281.    This incident did require a special switching move.      Cause Code:648  NARRI: 2 (3+5+0) x (3+0) = 48

Our tractor/trailer was westbound on I-70 in a heavy rain storm.  A 4-wheeler was passing our unit and lost control, first hitting our drive axle, then spinning around and hitting the pressure builder coil on the rear of the trailer just in front of the trailer tandems.  The 4-wheeler then hit the median barrier and spun into the right ditch.  Our unit stayed on the highway and pulled to shoulder.  Damage to pressure builder caused a leak of nitrogen from the trailer.  Ohio State Patrol escorted our unit to a vacant road off the interstate and the whole load of liquid nitrogen was vaporized to allow for safe transport of our unit to it's home terminal in Toledo.
column169: In this case, the fault of the accident was with the other party.  Better education on driving in adverse weather conditions would be good for all.

column168: A shipment containing polychlorinated biphenyl debris (transformer carcasses and bushings) was offered for transportation via rail.  During the course of transportation, the rail car was received at Clean Harbor’s Clive, Utah facility where the material was transferred from the rail car into dump trailers for the final leg of transportation activities (the intended waste management facility is not rail served).  At the conclusion of the transfer operation where the material was moved from the rail car into the dump trailers, residual liquid that was not identified at the time of initial loading or transfer escaped from the transformer carcasses onto the contained vehicle loading area.   Facility personnel immediately initiated a response action that involved the containment and collection of all material released from the transport vehicle.  All material that was collected was placed into suitable non bulk packages along with all clean –up debris.  The affected area was decontaminated and all decontamination medial was containerized for disposal as well.  Once the clean –up was complete, facility personnel re secured the dump trailer and this vehicle, along with all clean-up debris were transported to the intended waste management facility where it was disposed of.
column169: A review of the incident identified that cause of this incident can be attributed to small amounts of residual liquid remaining in individual transformer carcasses and which escaped from the transformers and mixed with the debris being transported for disposal.  Once the rail car was unloaded, this residual liquid pooled on the bottom of the dump trailer where it escaped from the rear seal of the cargo carrying portion.      In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper of the material is investigating the preparation and loading of this particular shipment as it was supposed to only container fully drained transformers and related debris.  Appropriate corrective actions will e taken to insure that any debris sent for transportation is free of all residual liquids.  In addition, the facility that prepared the dump trailer for continuing transportation has reviewed the incident with the loading personnel and has reviewed the steps necessary to properly secure an end dump.  One suspected contributing cause of this incident was a rear door seal that was not properly secured.  This rear seal allowed the residual liquid to escape from the package onto the contained loading area. Facility personnel will insure that rear door seals are inspected prior to closure to insure that the area between the door and the gasket is free of all debris that could cause the closure device to seal properly.

column169: BETTER BLOCKING AND BRACING OF TOTES WHEN LOADING.  DRIVER CHECKING LOAD BY OPENING DOOR WHEN FOUR HEAVY TOTES ARE LOADED.  WATCH SPEED WHEN TURNING CORNER ONTO RAMP. ALL TOTES MUST BE BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT AND FALLING OVER WHILE UNIT IS MOVING.  USE LOAD LOCK BARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING.  PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDSAHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.

column168: THE VEHICLE OWNED AND OPERATED BY BUMGARNER OIL CO. WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON STAR TOWN RD.  THE RIGHT REAR TANDEM WHEELS ON THE TANK TRAILER LEFT THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT, BUT COULD NOT AND THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED.  THE TANK TRAILER CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 7700 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  THE STAR TOWN ROAD WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY SIX HOURS TO FACILITATE THE OFF-LOADING OF DIESEL FUEL IN THE TANK TRAILER, UPRIGHTING OF THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE, ETC.                                                                                APPROXIMATELY 2200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE RELEASED FROM THE DOME LIDS OF THE OF THE TANK TRAILER DURING THE INCIDENT.  THE RELEASED FUEL IMPACTED THE PAVED ROADWAY SURFACE AND ADJACENT UNPAVED AREAS.  THE FLOW OF FUEL FROM THE DAMAGED TANK TRAILER LASTED APPROXIMATELY 1.5 HOURS FROM THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT UNTIL FUEL IN THE TANKER COULD BE OFF-LOADED. SUBSEQUENT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES WERE PEROFMRED, WHICH INCLUDED THE EXCAVATION OF PETROLEUM-IMPACTED SOIL. NEITHER GROUNDWATER NOR SURFACE WATER BODIES WERE IMPACTED BY THE SUBJECT RELEASE.THE RELEASE DID NOT RESULT IN AN EVACUATION OF RESIDENTS.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS INJURED, BUT NOT HOSPITALIZED.  THERE WERE NO OTHER INJURIES OR FATALITIES.

column169: BE AWARE OF THE SURROUNDINGS!  RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, BEING AWARE OF THE  SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! column168: Improper blocking/bracing contributed to a load shift in transit resulting in a hazmat spill that was detected when the container de-ramped in Portland, OR.  Approximately seven (7) gallons of corrosive liquid, basic, organic, n.o.s.(ethanol amine) Class 8, packing group II was found to be leaking from the container (cofc).  Container was taken to the hazmat pit by rail personnel.  Upon inspection of the interior of the container several pallets of hazardous and non-hazardous materials were found to have load shifted.  Approximately 85 total gallons of ethanol amine were discovered to have spilled, the majority still in the container, intermixed with non-haz floor sealer.  Hazmat contractor was contracted by J.B. Hunt to conduct hazmat containment; contractor dispatched subcontractor to the site to conduct the clean-up efforts.  Photos obtained by subcontractor revealed minimal-to-no load blocking and bracing had been conducted by the shipper.  Subsequent investigation by J.B. Hunt personnel and by the load consigner, Staples, led to a recommendation to the shipper (Carroll Company) to review their loading practices.
column169: This was the first of two similiar incidents involving the same shipper occuring withing an approxiametly two week timespan.  Both incidents were due to improper blocking/bracing.  This issue has been addressed with the shipper and with the consigner; additionally the railroad has begun to inspect shipments originating from this carrier.  Shipper has been advised by both J.B. Hunt and Staples how to properly block & brace shipments in the future in order to comply with DOT regulation #177.834(a)
