column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. accepted a shipment of a hazardous waste solid, n.o.s. (K049) generated from the cleaning of a tank that had contained slop oil emulsion solids.  At the time the shipment was accepted for transportation, the load was inspected and no evidence of heat or vapors were identified.  During the course of the trip, the driver observed a small amount of smoke coming from under the roll-off’s closure device.  The driver immediately pulled off the roadway and identified that the solid material appeared to be smoldering (please note that at no time were flames visual.  Part 4, section 30 indicates fire as one of the results but it is important to clarify that the load was smoldering and not engulfed in flames).  At this point, the driver placed the container on the ground and removed the power unit from the area.  Once this was accomplished, local emergency services, the shipper and the driver’s home dispatcher were notified of the situation.  The local Fire Department, A representative from the Texas DOT and response crews from both the transporter and shipper attended the scene and upon arrival, it was determined that the best course of action was to cover the material with a fire fighting foam.  During this operation, the road was closed by the local authorities as a precaution.   Once secured and it was determined that the smoldering material was extinguished, the TX DOT requested that the container be rejected back to the shippers location.  This was accomplished without incident.  While pending approval to move the container, notifications were also made to the National Response Center and the Texas Department of Environmental Quality.  Representatives from these 2 agencies also arrived at the scene to observe the response activities.  Please note that amount of material released is only an estimate as the only visible release was the smoke released as the material smoldered.
column169: At the time the material was inspected for transportation, no evidence of heat and/or smoke was observed.  As a result of the incident, however, the approval to ship this waste stream has been suspended pending the results of an internal investigation being performed by the shipper.  As of this time, the results of the investigation are not available.  A supplemental report will be prepared once the shipper’s investigation is complete.

column169: BETTER BRACING AND PLACING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DRUMS.  BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS!  RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  CHECK BRAKES FOR PROPER AND SAFE USE.  IF ATTACHMENTS USED FOR THE FORKLIFT ARE IMPROPERLY WORKING, THEY MUST BE REMOVED FRROM SERVICE AND BE REPAIRED OR TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PERMANENTLY.  MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFE USE FOR ALL.  WHEN ENTERING OR EXITING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS, OR TOTES LOADED OR STACKED ON THE FLOOR; ON A PLATFORM AND/OR HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIAFT.  DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK.     HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE        AND PUNCTURING.  LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE.  EMPLOYEE GIVEN COACHING ON LOADING AND DOCK AWARENESS.

DAVISON FUEL TRUCK DRIVER WAS AT A DELIVERY LOCATION (BAHIA MAR MANNA) AND WAS TRASFERRING DIESEL FUEL FROM TRANSPORT TRUCK TO THE CUSTOMER'S ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  TANK CAPACITY WAS 8000 GALLONS.  CUSTOMER HAD ORDERED 5000 GALS - HOWEVER TANK COULD NOT HOLD ALL PRODUCT THAT WAS ORDERED.  PRODUCT OVER FLOWED FROM TANK ONTO GROUND.  DRIVER STOPPED THE PRODUCT TRANSFER WHEN HE OBSERVED THIS AND WORKED TO CONTAIN SPILLED PRODUCT.  NOTE THAT TANK IS LOCATED BY WATER - THIS IS A MARINA - SOME PRODUCT DID FLOW INTO WATER - HOWEVER IT WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED BY BOOMS.  THE WATER WAS IN A BOAT FUELING SLIP WITH CONCRETE WALLS AND A BOAT THAT WAS CONTRACTED TO THE BP GULF OF MEXICO SPILL TRANSPORT WAS AT MARINA FOR FUELING.  THAT CREW SAW THE OVERFLOW AND IMMEDIATELY DEPLOYED THE BOOMS AND ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  A VACUMN TRUCK WAS BROUGHT IN AND ALL OILY WATER REMOVED THAT SAME DAY.  THE HIGH-LEVEL OVER FILL ALARM ON THE STORAGE TANK FAILED TO OPEN AND THERE WAS- NO LEVEL CAUSE ON THIS TANK TO WARN OF LEVEL.
column169: THERE WAS NO WAY FOR DRIVER TO CHECK LEVEL USING A CAUSE STICK.  THERE WAS NO LEVEL GADGET ON THE TANK.  THERE WAS NO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM (DYKE) AROUMD TANK TO CONTAIN ANY SPILLAGE ON OVERFLOW EVEN THOUGH THIS TANK WAS NEAR A BODY OF WATER.  HUMAN ERROR CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT, HOWEVER I FEEL THAT THERE SHOULD BE SOME TYPE OF READABLE LEVEL GADGET ON THE TANK ITSELF (AT THE TANKS IMMEIDATE PHYSICAL LOCATION)  ALSO IN SITUATIONS USE THIS WHERE A.S.T.'S ARE LOCATED NEAR A BODY OF WATER IT SHOULD BE REQUIRED TO HAVE SOME TYPE OF SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM - (A DYKE) TO CONTAIN ANY ACCIDENTAL SPILLAGE.

column168: Intermodal tank container SNTU 400189 (an import shipment from China that arrived earlier on a sailing vessel) was staged at the intermodal loading track Intermodal tank container SNTU 400189 (an import shipment from China that arrived earlier on a sailing vessel) was staged at the intermodal loading track next to the intermodal railcar it was scheduled to be loaded upon.  Apparently, an unknown vehicle struck the front end of SNTU 400189's attached chassis which caused the chassis to skid sideways collapsing one of the chassis' support stanchions.  SNTU 400189 came to rest leaning against the rail flatcar. The lean angle of SNTU 400189 forced liquid commodity out from its pressure/vacuum relief valve at the top of SNTU 400189.  The product release stopped when SNTU 400189 was up-righted by BNSF contract responders.  The chassis was then connected to a hostler truck's trailer hitch to steady SNTU 400189 until it was loaded atop another suitable chassis.  Product spillage on the impacted rail flatcar was cleaned.  Clay absorbent was applied onto the ground spillage atop the asphalt.  Solidified spillage with absorbent was placed into 55-gallon disposal drums along with other spent cleaning materials for appropriate future disposal.

column168: On Tuesday, June 8, 2010, at 1310 hours EST, Southern Refrigerated Transport contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Project Manager, Mr. Wayne Koszegi, CHMM to request assistance with a paint spill. The spill occurred at the PPG Industries facility located at 4820 Mehurin Street in Jefferson, LA.  SRT advised that the spill was noticed when paint was seen dripping onto the pavement.    Utilizing A•C•T’s pre-approved nationwide database of emergency response teams, A•C•T contracted with United States Environmental Services to assess and conduct cleanup operations, as necessary.    A•C•T and its representatives are committed to providing a safe work environment for all of its employees and clients.  An important part of the A•C•T Contractor Safety Program is contractor safety prequalification.  To qualify to work on an A•C•T site, all companies must successfully complete the safety prequalification process and meet A•C•T’s level of safety excellence.  Our response team utilized on this spill has met the minimum requirements to be a subcontractor for A•C•T.    Upon arrival at the site, our response team reported that the trailer was full and would need to be off-loaded prior to assessment.  A forklift at the facility was used to remove undamaged product in order to access the source of the release.  It was discovered that 24 – 5 gallon pails of paint had come off their pallets due to a broken keeper rail.  SRT requested that the pails be over-packed and left on the trailer.  The damaged paint cans were removed from the rear of the trailer and placed into six (6) 55-gallon drums and then reloaded onto the trailer.  The responders reported that three pallets required disposal, and these were also placed back onto the trailer.  Much of the paint had begun to dry and was difficult to remove.  In an attempt to remove as much of the paint as possible sorbent pads were used to soak up the still wet paint.  Granular sorbents were then applied and brushed into the trailer floor.  The paint-contaminated granular sorbent was collected using a vacuum.  The response team finished wiping down the back of the trailer of the liquid paint and hand excavated the paint impacted rocks and soil from under the trailer, which was placed into 55-gallon drums.  All damaged product and cleanup debris was reloaded onto the trailer.    On June 9, 2010, SRT requested that the previously overpacked, damaged paint cans be removed from the trailer and properly disposed of.  The vehicle had traveled into Texas at this point and our network subcontractor Milstead Environmental was contacted to facilitate the offload and disposal of the material.  ACT directed the SRT driver to the Milstead Environmental facility where the activities would take place.  Using a forklift our response team offloaded the pallets of overpacked 55-gallon drums and staged them at their facility pending waste profiling and transport and disposal.  The trailer was secured and the SRT vehicle

column168: Pasadena CA. with his tank truck and trailer loaded with 8,600 gallons of gasoline.  When the driver was taking a curve near the Bob Hope Drive off ramp his trailer rolled to the right.  The driver contacted the dispatch supervisor who in turn alerted Pacific Tank Lines management.  CHP was on the scene within two minutes of the incident. Shortly after, Fire Departments from multiple cities also arrived on scene.  Pacific Tank Lines Operations Team immediately dispatched their Hazmat and Environmental Team.  A pump truck was also dispatched to the location to assist if needed.  Pacific Tank Lines Safety team arrived within 30 minutes of the incident and began coordinating the vehicle recovery and spill response with all local agencies that were on site.  As result of the incident 4,500 gallons of gasoline was spilled to the ground.  Pacific Tank Lines, Inc. commenced an incident investigation. Pacific Tank Lines, Inc. investigation team determined that the most likely scenario was that the trailer drifted from the path of travel and dropped a wheel into a small storm water gutter running along the edge of the freeway immediately to the right of the lane.  As a consequence of the driver’s actions in attempting to steer the trailer back to the lane of travel, the trailer rolled over, sustaining considerable damage to the tank and causing a spill of 4,500 gallons of gasoline.  The product flowed from the highway into a rain water runoff catch basin below the highway.  The product then ran from the catch basin onto the city street and flowed into an aggregate catch basin in a city park.   The damage to the trailer consisted of three tears in the side bulkhead from the trailer sliding 687’ on the roadway. After the emergency response the vehicle was up righted and was inspected. It was found that there was no other damage to the trailer and could be driven from the scene, Pacific Tank Lines, Inc. decided to tow the trailer to a designated terminal for further inspection.
column169: Pacific Tank Lines, Inc. has implemented new driving instructions for traveling on SR-134 in Burbank CA. to include that drivers are to travel in the #2 lane only when on the portion of the 134. This will be documented in the required journey plan for the route. Pacific Tank Lines, Inc. does conduct roll over training for all of its drivers and will continue to conduct the company required training.   Pacific Tank Lines would like to recommend that the city of Burbank CA. look into the option of removing the small culvert in an attempt to avoid another roll over type incident from occurring in that section of SR-134.

SHIPPER REQUESTED THEM TO FILL OUT THE FORM AND SEND IT ONCE MORE.                                                                               06/23/2010 SHIPPER PROCEEDED AN AIR TRANSPORTATION FROM LAX TO NRT (NARITA AIRPORT, JAPAN) WITH AWB:205-0725 2711 (EXHIBIT B), ONBOARD OUR FLIGHT#: NH005.  SHIPPER RECEIVED THE SIGNED DG STATEMENT MENTIONED ABOVE (EXHIBIT A).  THE KIT PRODUCT ARRIVED AT NRT FOLLOWING DAY.                                                                                08/09 - 13/2010 UPON A REQUEST FROM "CONSIGNEE," ANA TRADING CO., LTD (TOKYO, JAPAN), SHIPPER REQUESTED THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER TO PROVIDE ALL THE APPLICABLE MSDS FOR THE KIT COMPONENTS AND LET THEM MAKE SURE THAT THE KIT WAS NON-DG.  THEN, THEY CONFIRMED THAT THE KIT WAS NON-DG.                                                                                 08/13 - 16/2010 AFTER HAVING MSDS (EXHIBIT C) REVIEWED, SHIPPER CONCLUDED THAT ONE OF THE COMPONENTS (CANNED AIR) WAS REGULATED BY IATA DGR AS "CONSUMER COMMODITY," CLASS 9, MISCELLANEOUS, ID#8000, AND REPORTED IT TO CONSIGNEE.                           08/17/2010 CONSIGNEE INFORMED OUR TOKYO OFFICE THE CONCLUSION MENTIONED ABOVE.                                                                              08/19/2010 SHIPPER OFFICIALLY INFORMED US (LAX OFFICE) THE CONCLUSION MENTIONED ABOVE.
column169: ANA has met with and insisted to our company material shipper, ANA Trading Corp USA, to rigidly check all the applicable MSDS to make sure there is no hidden DG included when "Kit" or "Set" products with multiple components are received. column168: Driver arrived at delivery location for delivery of no lead gasoline; positioned vehicle for delivery and stuck product tanks for capacity and capacity calculations. Driver then proceeded to set up his off load equipment preparatory to the unloading process. Driver advised that he was setting up to deliver two (2) compartments of gasoline product off of his transport trailer; that he connected two (2) delivery drop fittings into the connections to the drop fittings of the facilities two (2) no lead gasoline storage tanks; that he pulled two (2) product hoses off trailer and onto the ground; that he pulled two vapor recovery hoses off trailer onto ground; that he made connection of the shorter of the two product hoses to the drop fitting to the facility storage tank and also connected it to the unload head on the trailer; he then connected the longer of his two delivery hoses to the unload head on the trailer (However, the error was that the driver had failed to connect the “longer” hose to the second NL tank delivery fitting — it was left un-connected lying on the ground next to the tank drop fitting); drive then started flow of product off trailer. Driver states he immediately saw product coming out of the end of the “un-connected” long product hose onto the ground and that he shut the trailer valves off to cease the flow of product. Driver advised that no more than 3 to 4 seconds could have passed from the time he started product flow! observed product coming out of the un-connected hose and when he had shut valves off and product flow ceased. (Using the average gravity product flow rate of 240 gallons per minute (4 gallons per second); it was felt that the no more than 20 gallons of product was spilled). Driver called our operations staff and call forwarded to director of safety. Driver was advised to place call to 911 for immediate fire department response and to advise customer clerk in attendance to make appropriate notification to their personnel. On-site inspection was that some of the product had entered into a storm water drain adjacent to the off load area at the station. Personnel from local fire department determined product had entered into a basin area immediately adjacent to the parking lot. Environmental response contractor was summoned to boom off and contain and product, storm drain and lines were drained with any free product removed by vac truck. Ditch line of the basin area was walked and any residual product was padded and removed. Containment booms were installed overnight to contain any residual product that have still existed in the storm water drain, lines, and basin area. On site activity was coordinated with communication of local OHEPA representative and it was determined that after a heavy rainfall event that occurred the evening of the next day that any residual product had been displaced and the cleanup activities were granted as complete.
column169: Interviews with driver both during, and post the event, define that the cause of the error to be driver error. Driver admitted he basically failed to connect one of the product hoses (that run from connection to the unload heads on our trailer to the drop fittings used to connect and place product into the facility storage tank) that he got out of his normal routine while setting up to unload and thru his own inattention and failure to follow proper procedures cased the spill event to occur. As a note, the hoses and fittings were checked and found to be in normal condition.   Proper unloading procedures are incorporated into our driver safety/training manual in detail for the entire process. Each driver undergoes initial classroom training followed up by field training by a driver trainer. When any incident occurs it is reviewed in detail with the driver and a determination of cause is rendered. If deemed warranted, a driver will undergo re-training respective to the concerns presented by any incident in order to prevent recurrence of like incidents. We present incident summaries along with cause and prevention to our drivers/staff on a regular basis, such as during our quarterly safety meetings

column168: DELIVERY DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING A INDUSTRIAL BATTERY WHEN THE WEB STRAPPING BROKE AS THE DRIVER WAS TURNING THE CORNER CAUSING THE BATTERY TO FALL OFF THE TRUCK.
column169: FROM JUNE 8, 2010, GOING FORWARD ALL BATTERIES WILL BE DOUBLE STRAPPED NO MATER OF THE SIZE OR THE WEIGHT.  STRAPS ARE INSPECTED DAILY FOR WEAR AND TEAR BEFORE THEY ARE USED TO SECURE FREIGHT.

column168: Driver was unloading using his product pump. he also had a 3x2" adapter with a bleeder valve built in (ball valve)for product sampling. during the unloading process the vibration opened the ball valve and allowed product to spill into a catch bucked the driver had positioned under the pump the driver did dot know the valve had opened until the bucked overfilled and the product spilled onto the containment pad. The driver discovered the spill and shut down the pump. He notified the operator and assisted in cleaning up the spill. driver switched out the fitting and continued with the delivery.
column169: The driver was disciplined for this incident. And was instructed to check his fittings and have them maintained and repaired if necessary. he was also instructed on how to secure valves from inadvertently opening.

column168: AMG DRIVER WAS DRIVING ON HIGHWAY 501 SOUTH ON JUNE 14 2010 AT 11:15 IN DILLON SC. HE WAS COLLIDED BY A CAR IN OUR LANE HEAD ON. THE UNIT (TRACTOR & TANKER) WENT INTO A DITCH LAYING ON THE PASSENGER SIDE. THE UNIT WAS TOO HEAVY TO GET OUT OF THE DITCH. THE TRAILER WAS FULL OF LIQUID CRYOGENIC OXYGEN. WE HAD A CRYOGENIC MECHANIC ON SITE WHO DUMPED THE LOAD TO ATMOSPHERE. IT WAS ABOUT 3400 GALLONS OF O2 PUT BACK INTO THE AIR. MECHACNIC WAITED UNTIL ALL WAS VAPORIZED BEFORE LEAVING THE SITE.
column169: DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE ACCIDENT THIS WAS THE ONLY THING THAT MADE SENSE. I DON'T HAVE ANY SUGGESTIONS ON THIS INCIDENT.
